ationship between technical innovations and theatrical events that incorporated scientific content into dramatic productions. Focusing on Spanish dramas between 1500 and 1700, through the birth and development of its playhouses and coliseums and the phenomenal success of its major writers, this collection addresses a unique phenomenon through the most popular, versatile, and generous medium of the time. The contributors tackle subjects and disciplines as diverse as alchemy, optics, astronomy, acoustics, geometry, mechanics, and mathematics to reveal how theatre could be used to deploy scientific knowledge. While Science on Stage contributes to cultural and performance studies it also engages with issues of censorship, the effect of the Spanish Inquisition on the circulation of ideas, and the influence of the Eastern traditions in Spain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aSpanish dramayClassical period, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aTheaterzSpainxHistoryy16th century. 0aTheaterzSpainxHistoryy17th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / Spanish & Portuguese.2bisacsh  aearly modern Spanish science.  aearly modern Spanish theatre.  aearly modern drama.  ahistory of science.  ainnovations in theatre.  aliterary studies.  aperformance.  aplayhouses.  astagecraft.  atechnology on the stage.1 aAlbuixech, Lourdes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAncell, Matthew G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía-Reidy, Alejandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKimmel, Seth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPortuondo, María M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRupp, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul